The finite matrix dimension  provides both a short-distance and
low-momentum cutoff simultaneously, because in matrix regularizations
of noncommutative field theory the UV and IR divergences are not
clearly separated and one needs to regulate them both at the same
time . There are, however, many different ways to
take the large  limit of the matrix model with partition function
(), and we need to decide which is the appropriate
one that captures the true non-perturbative physics of the original
continuum field theory.

The large  limit is meaningful only when the entropy from the
growth in the number of integration variables is compensated by a
large action. In matrix models, an action of order , typically of the form
, is necessary to balance quantum
fluctuations . Hence we need to require that
 as  in (). In other
words, we must take the large  limit while keeping fixed the ratio
^2=N/4 ,
which simply defines the  limit of the noncommutative
field theory. This limit is a generic feature of the matrix
regularization of noncommutative field theories .
The important feature of the model with a background magnetic field is
that the whole action has a nice matrix representation, in contast to
other noncommutative field theories, in which the kinetic term has no
matrix representation , and to ordinary field theories with
background fields, in which the kinetic term is simple in the Landau basis,
but the interactions are complicated .

There are two important consequences of this correlated large  and
large  limit. First of all,
this limit is just the standard 't Hooft planar limit of the
matrix model. Secondly, the natural UV cutoff of the original
noncommutative field theory is the energy of the  Landau
level, which is  and stays finite 
as  goes to infinity. Thus the quantity () is the
true UV cutoff of the quantum field theory. This will be confirmed
below by explicit calculations. Since  as
, the spacing between Landau levels also vanishes. Thus
taking the limit described above is equivalent to filling the finite
energy interval  with infinitely many Landau
levels and an infinite density of states.

Thus the large  limit of the model defined by
() is a quantum field theory with a finite cutoff
whose exact solution is given by the 't Hooft limit of the complex
external field matrix model (). As an example, we
will explicitly compute the exact two-point function defined by
